name: Set of seven ramekins in blues & greens by Judy Jackson
description:
Based in New York City, Judy Jackson has been working as a potter for decades. Her collection includes dinnerware, bottle vases, planters, cookware, teapots, mugs, tumblers and ramekins in a variety of colors. Her handmade stoneware pieces are wheel thrown, slab built, slip cast or made combining these methods. Her matte glazes are dipped and poured before being oxidation-fired to a durable stoneware temperature. Judy says of her work, "All of my designs have evolved from simple respect for form, and the unending ability of clay to respond to my abilities to create forms I find pleasing."

The largest ramekin measures 9 1/2" length x 7" width x 2" h. All are oven safe for baking, and great for serving olives, fruit, crackers, dips, whatever you like!

name: Cardinal Bird Print on Wood by The Mincing Mockinbird
description:
Based in La Crescenta, California, The Mincing Mockingbird's impeccably painted images are at once realistic and surrealist. With a wide-ranging color palette, these evocative prints have a wonderful expressiveness and intensity. A close examination makes perceptible a subtle sense of incredulity, nobility, or ambivalence, capturing the unique characteristics and personalities of the subjects.

This Cardinal panel is a giclee print mounted on 1 5/8" deep birch from an original painting. It's 8" wide x 10" tall. A keyhole makes for easy wall display. Pick your favorite or design an eclectic grouping of your own.

name: Star Necklace with Diamond by Carla Caruso
description:
Local artist Carla Caruso graduated from RISD with a degree in glass sculpture. Over the years Carla worked with several glass artists, including collaboration on a line of glass jewelry. Finding her creative outlet in jewelry design, she founded Carla Caruso Jewelry in 2001. Totally self-taught, Carla's handmade jewelry retains a sculptural quality paired with a natural yet modern-minimalist aesthetic. Her collection has evolved over the years but the essence remains the same: handmade jewelry that wears beautifully.

This playful necklace features a three-dimensional 14k gold star pendant accented with .02 carat, G-H color, SI1 clarity diamond set in a 14k gold bezel. The pendant hangs from a darkly oxidized sterling silver cable chain measuring 16" with a lobster clasp.

name: Animal Farm Birdhouse by Wild Wings Literary Lodgings

name: Tall Maple Bowl by Three Wheel Studio
description:
Based in Pawtucket, Rhode Island, Dwo Wen Chen is the potter behind Three Wheel Studio. Born in Taiwan and educated at the Rhode Island School of Design, he uses hand-building and wheel-throwing techniques to create his beautifully formed stoneware pieces. Handmade and one of a kind, this brightly embellished stoneware bowl features bright red Japanese maple leaves.  The bowl measures approx. 7.5” high and the opening is 9.5” in diameter.  Finished with a clear, food-safe glaze, the pieces can go in the dishwasher and microwave.

name: Blue Flower Brooch by Joli Jewelry
description:
Jody Lyons began Joli Jewelry in 1984. With a love for the stylized periods of the 1920's-1960's, Jody's appreciation of all things vintage eventually developed into a colorful, witty and wearable line of jewelry. Because of the availability of her authentic components, Joli Jewelry only offers limited edition pieces.

Joli Jewelry is handmade in Brooklyn, NY using vintage glass, original plastics like celluloid and Bakelite, old metal findings, old French enamels and mother of pearl pieces. Found items such as buttons, buckles, trimming, perfume bottle top crystals, purse openers, fans and furniture handles as well as new semi-precious, glass and metal components are incorporated. This vintage plastic brooch measures approximately 2" wide and 3" long.

name: Elizabeth Warren Mug by Justin Rothshank
description:
Justin Rothshank is a ceramic artist working in Goshen, Indiana. His functional and decorative pottery utilizes custom-made laser decals, china paints, lusters and commercial decals for embellishment. Rothshank uses earthenware clay that is wheel-thrown before being fired in an electric kiln, often several times, to achieve the multiple layers of decals on some of his pieces.

Microwave and dishwasher safe, please note that no two pieces will be the same. Justin says he “particularly enjoys the organic edges and unique feel of each piece that I make.”  The mugs measure approx. 4” high and 3 ½” in diameter.

Made from discarded library books and other salvaged finds, these repurposed birdhouses are the ultimate in upcycling. David Vissat, the man behind Wild Wings Literary Lodgings, designs these delightful birdhouses using pages from the vintage hardcover books to decorate the outside, the books themselves as roofs and carefully selected corresponding perches as the perfect finishing touch.

These decoupage birdhouses are meant to complement indoor spaces on a bookshelf or mantle piece, rather than being exposed to the outdoor elements. Individually signed by the artist, they make a wonderful housewarming or wedding gift for your literary friends.  Each birdhouse measures approximately 7” long, 5.5” wide and 8.5” high at the peak.
